 the northern Italian Humiliati, the meaning of romance narratives centred around the departure of the hero or heroine from the natal hearth, the age at which later medieval English youngsters left home, how far they travelled and where they went, literary sources revealing the politicisation of the idea of the child, and the response of young, affluent females to homiletic literature and the iconography of the virgin martyrs in the later middle ages. Contributors: FRANCES E. ANDREWS, HELEN COOPER, P.J.P.GOLDBERG, SIMCHA GOLDIN, EDWARD F. JAMES, JUDITH JESCH, KIM M. PHILLIPS, MIKE TYLER, ROSALYNN VOADEN.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChildrenxHistoryy16th centuryzEurope. 0aChildrenxHistoryyTo 1500zEurope. 0aChildrenzEuropexHistoryy16th century. 0aChildrenzEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aSocial historyyMedieval, 500-1500. 0aYouthxHistoryy16th centuryzEurope. 0aYouthxHistoryyTo 1500zEurope. 0aYouthzEuropexHistoryy16th century. 0aYouthzEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 4aMedieval History. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Children's Studies.2bisacsh  aChaucer.  aIceland.  aVikings.  aYouth.  aromance.1 aAndrews, Frances, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrosnan, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldberg, P J P, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldberg, P J P, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGoldberg, P. J. P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldin, Simcha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldin, Simha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJames, 